{"id":"2205.07067","submitter":"Carlo A. Trugenberger","authors":"M. C. Diamantini, C. A. Trugenberger and V. M. Vinokur","title":"How planar superconductors cure their infrared divergences","comments":null,"journal-ref":"JHEP 10, 100 (2022)","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.supr-con hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Planar superconductors, thin films with thickness comparable to the\nsuperconducting coherence length, differ crucially from their bulk\ncounterparts. The Coulomb interaction is logarithmic up to distances exceeding\ntypical sample sizes and the Anderson-Higgs mechanism is ineffective to screen\nthe resulting infrared divergences of the resulting (2+1)-dimensional QED\nbecause the Pearl length is also typically larger than sample sizes. As a\nconsequence, the system decomposes into superconducting droplets with the\ntypical size of the coherence length. We show that the two possible phases of\nthe system match the two known mechanisms by which (2+1)-dimensional QED cures\nits infrared divergences, either by generating a mixed topological Chern-Simons\nmass or by magnetic monopole instantons. The former is realized in\nsuperconductors, the latter governs mirror-dual superinsulators. Planar\nsuperconductors are thus described by a topological Chern-Simons gauge (TCSG)\ntheory which replaces the Ginzburg-Landau model in two dimensions. In the TCSG\nmodel, the Higgs field is absent. Accordingly, in planar superconductors\nAbrikosov vortices do not form, and only Josephson vortices with no normal core\ncan emerge.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 14 May 2022 13:47:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 18 Oct 2022 08:15:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-19"}
